A '''class II gene''' is a type of [[gene]] that codes for a [[protein]]. Class II genes are [[transcription (genetics)|transcribed]] by [[RNAP|RNAP II]].

Class II genes have a [[promoter (biology)|promoter]] that may contain a [[TATA box]]. 

Basal transcription of class II genes requires the formation of a [[Transcription preinitiation complex|preinitiation complex]].

They are transcribed by RNA polymerase II, include both intron and exon, and code for polypeptide.

[[Major histocompatibility complex]] (MHC) class II genes are important in the immune response.<ref>{{cite journal| pmc=2987717 | pmid=19890353 | doi=10.1038/gene.2009.83 | volume=11 | issue=2 | title=Regulation of major histocompatibility complex class II gene expression, genetic variation and disease | year=2010 | journal=Genes Immun | pages=99–112 | last1 = Handunnetthi | first1 = L | last2 = Ramagopalan | first2 = SV | last3 = Ebers | first3 = GC | last4 = Knight | first4 = JC}}</ref>

